It is a chilly Saturday morning in a church hall made from corrugated iron in Hammarsdale township, west of Durban. Women are sitting on chairs and pieces of foam lined against the wall while some children are playing outside. They are among the thousands of people who have been left homeless and bereaved by the recent floods in parts of KwaZulu-Natal.



Lindiwe Jileka, 58, has experienced every mother’s worst nightmare: losing a child. Her loss is compounded by the deaths of four of her grandchildren, who also died in the floods.



On 11 April, her daughter Bonakele Jileka, 38, was sleeping in a bedroom with two of her three children, Yenzokuhle, 10, and Elimiyo, 2, in their home in Hammarsdale. Lindiwe was sleeping in another room with two of her grandchildren, Akhile, 13, and Zekhethelo, 10, whose mother Sindiswe, 38, was at work. The family heard a sudden thump as the walls collapsed and water rushed in, carrying with it large rocks and pieces of steel from the railway line behind their home. The family who share a yard with the Jilekas rushed over to help. They could pull out only Lindiwe. 



<img data-attachment-id="158315" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/burials-bring-more-pain-for-durban-flood-victims/kzn-floods_va002/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002.jpg" data-orig-size="2362,1575" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;6.3&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D850&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;April 2022: Bonakele&#039;s sister Hlengiwe Zulu inspects the broken railway that runs behind the house where the five family members died. Photograph by Madelene Cronj\u00e9&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1650714450&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;42&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;200&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.0025&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="KZN-floods_va002" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;April 2022: Bonakele&#8217;s sister Hlengiwe Zulu inspects the broken railway that runs behind the house where the five family members died. Photograph by Madelene Cronjé&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002-1440x960.jpg" loading="lazy" width="2362" height="1575" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-158315" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002.jpg 2362w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002-1920x1280.jpg 1920w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va002-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 2362px) 100vw, 2362px" />23 April 2022: Bonakele’s sister Hlengiwe Zulu stands on the bank of the broken railway line that runs behind the house in Hammarsdale where the five Jileka family members died. A part of it collapsed and fell on their house during the heavy rains.



She and her family felt a measure of relief when they heard the government would provide money to help with funeral costs. But those promises have not materialised, forcing her to scramble to find the money elsewhere.



The Jileka family is one of more than 12 000 families whose houses partially or completely collapsed in the floods. “We don’t know what’s going on right now,” said Nontobeko Ngcobo, 34, Lindiwe’s daughter. “We were told the government would provide R15 000 for each deceased person, then they said it was R20 000. The local councillor came here and asked us for documents, including bank details, and he said the money will be in within 24 hours.



“The next thing we hear is that money will be sent to burial companies instead. Now our issue is we were covered with Icebolethu Funerals. Bonakele was paying premiums that covered her and her two deceased children, so if that R60 000 is sent to the funeral home it doesn’t help us with anything [because Icebolethu was going to cover the funeral costs anyway from their premiums].”



<img data-attachment-id="158317" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/burials-bring-more-pain-for-durban-flood-victims/kzn-floods_va003/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003.jpg" data-orig-size="2362,1575" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;5&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D850&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;April 2022: Bonakele&#039;s sister, Nontobeko stands at the ruins where her sister died. Photograph by Madelene Cronj\u00e9&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1650712927&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;50&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;125&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.0015625&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="KZN-floods_va003" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;April 2022: Bonakele&#8217;s sister, Nontobeko stands at the ruins where her sister died. Photograph by Madelene Cronjé&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003-1440x960.jpg" loading="lazy" width="2362" height="1575" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-158317" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003.jpg 2362w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003-1920x1280.jpg 1920w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va003-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 2362px) 100vw, 2362px" />23 April 2022: Bonakele Jileka’s sister Nontobeko Ngcobo stands in the ruins where her sister died.



According to the family, Icebolethu Funerals asked for R18 000 to bury Akhile and Zekhethelo as their mother didn’t have any funeral cover. They found it difficult to raise the money and had heard no word on the progress of the government funding.



The local ward councillor, Malulu Sikhakhane, said he doesn’t agree with the decision to pay funeral companies directly. “Our people are struggling now and it makes the councillors look bad, but we were just writing reports on those affected and other decisions are made at the top,” he said. 




