" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va004-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va004-1440x960.jpg" loading="lazy" width="2362" height="1575" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va004.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-158319" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va004.jpg 2362w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va004-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va004-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va004-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va004-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va004-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va004-1920x1280.jpg 1920w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va004-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va004-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/KZN-floods_va004-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 2362px) 100vw, 2362px" />23 April 2022: Junior Jileka and his aunt Thenjiwe Zulu. Junior was in the house when the floods destroyed it, but survived the ordeal. He lost his mother and his two siblings.



Nontobeko, who gave a speech on behalf of the family, said: “We want to say rest in peace to our sister and our children. We were not a rich family, but we were happy together. We are consoled that you left Junior [12] with us here. He is ours. Ze, Nana, rest in peace, babies.”



Lindiwe penned a short message that read: “I don’t have words. I am out of words because of the amount of pain I have felt. I will never forget it. I have to accept and say go well because I saw your lives perish right in front of my eyes, so I can only say farewell and rest well, my daughter and my grandchildren.”



Bonakele had recently graduated from Coastal College with a diploma in electrical engineering. Her lecturer and friend Sinenhlanhla Ngcobo described her as dedicated, generous with her time and knowledge, and a pillar in her classroom.




